					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/benjamin-stokes" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(826567); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=826567&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610250342" alt="Benjamin Stokes" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=826567)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/benjamin-stokes" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(826567); return false;" >Benjamin Stokes</a></span> <span class="odate time_1435360010 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">26 Jun 2015 23:06</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2325887">
									

<p>I really, REALLY want to like this, and to some extent I do&#8230; But there's something about the writing style that bugs me. The quotes are all quite long, with little to no descriptors of the speaker's manner and paralanguage; in other words, it reads like a transcription of a written conversation (a particularly well-thought-out text message exchange, maybe).</p>
<p>That stylistic approach would be fine, of course, except that the lack of description leads to the dialogue getting bogged down as it attempts to tell rather than show. People keep saying things that they shouldn't have to, which makes every line feel exposition-ey and breaks immersion.</p>
<p>The actual story is fine, though, even if I couldn't lose myself in it. I'm gonna neutral vote for now.</p>

							</div>

								
